comments.body:
Thanks for looking into it @marcofleon! If there are no operational concerns adding the test cases, I'm happy with it.

I guess if we keep this, the `uint256::FromHex()` asserts have become superfluous and could be removed. Shouldn't make a meaningful performance impact (since they're called much less often than the `FromUserHex()` asserts, so it's more of a thing to keep the test code lean.

<details>
<summary>git diff on 6fa4c92e4c</summary>

```diff
diff --git a/src/test/fuzz/hex.cpp b/src/test/fuzz/hex.cpp
index 1109186a8f..71518f626a 100644
--- a/src/test/fuzz/hex.cpp
+++ b/src/test/fuzz/hex.cpp
@@ -28,12 +28,7 @@ FUZZ_TARGET(hex)
     if (IsHex(random_hex_string)) {
         assert(ToLower(random_hex_string) == hex_data);
     }
-    if (uint256::FromHex(random_hex_string)) {
-        assert(random_hex_string.length() == 64);
-        assert(Txid::FromHex(random_hex_string));
-        assert(Wtxid::FromHex(random_hex_string));
-        assert(uint256::FromUserHex(random_hex_string));
-    }
+    (void)uint256::FromHex(random_hex_string);
     if (auto result{uint256::FromUserHex(random_hex_string)}) {
         const auto result_string{result->ToString()};
         assert(result_string.length() == 64);

```
</details>

